ok please fix

Below is the corrected version. Since you're already receiving each value as a parameter, the unnecessary destructuring of a non-existent data object has been removed:

js
static create(
  environment,
  issuer_name,
  issuer_id,
  iisc,
  bin,
  binProduct,
  pan_length,
  test_card_type,
  confirm_secured_connection,
  contact_person,
  contact_email,
  status
) {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const sql = `
      INSERT INTO issuers (
        environment, issuer_name, issuer_id, iisc, bin, binProduct, pan_length,
        test_card_type, confirm_secured_connection, contact_person,
        contact_email, status
      )
      VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)
    `;

    db.query(
      sql,
      [
        environment,
        issuer_name,
        issuer_id,
        iisc,
        bin,
        binProduct,
        pan_length,
        test_card_type,
        confirm_secured_connection,
        contact_person,
        contact_email,
        status,
      ],
      (err, result) => {
        if (err) reject(err);
        else resolve(result.insertId); // Return the newly created record's ID
      }
    );
  });
}

This version directly uses the function parameters in the query without attempting to destructure from an undefined variable.

Explanation

  • Controlled Form Data:
    All the fields now have corresponding state in the formData object. A generic handleInputChange function updates the state based on the field’s name attribute.

  • Validation Logic:
    The validate function checks that required fields are not empty, that the PAN Length contains only numbers, and that the contact email is valid. If a field fails validation, an error message is stored in the errors state.

  • Error Display:
    Each input (or group of inputs) now displays an error message (using Bootstrap’s text-danger class) if its corresponding key exists in the errors state.

  • Form Submission:
    When the form is submitted (via the "Add Card" button), handleValidate prevents the default behavior, runs the validation, and either shows errors or alerts that the form is valid.

This should give you a good starting point for validating all form fields and displaying error messages below each input.

const handleValidate = (e) => { e.preventDefault(); const validationErrors = validate(); if (Object.keys(validationErrors).length > 0) { alert(validationErrors.bind(validationErrors || [])); //setErrors(validationErrors); } else { setErrors({}); alert("Form is valid!"); // Proceed with further actions (e.g., form submission) } }; here can we show error in alert box ?

Yes, you can display all errors in an alert box. One common approach is to join all the error messages into a single string and pass that string to alert. For example:

js
const handleValidate = (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  const validationErrors = validate();
  if (Object.keys(validationErrors).length > 0) {
    const errorMessages = Object.values(validationErrors).join("\n");
    alert(errorMessages);
    // Alternatively, you could set errors in state: setErrors(validationErrors);
  } else {
    setErrors({});
    alert("Form is valid!");
    // Proceed with further actions (e.g., form submission)
  }
};

This code collects all error messages from the validationErrors object, joins them with a newline between each message, and then displays them in an alert box.
